    understandingLevels: {
        novice: {
            characteristics: [
                "Can name most major biomes but confuses tundra with desert (both dry) and boreal forest with temperate forest",
                "Associates biomes with continents rather than climate (e.g. 'rainforest = South America' rather than 'rainforest = warm and wet')",
                "Cannot position biomes correctly on the Whittaker diagram",
                "Describes adaptations as organism 'choices' rather than products of natural selection",
                "Conflates desertification (human-driven) with natural desert formation",
                "Assumes tropical rainforest soils are fertile because the biome is so productive"
            ],
            immediateNextSteps: [
                "Before memorising any biome facts: draw a 2×2 grid with axes of temperature (cold/warm) and rainfall (dry/wet). Place each biome in the correct quadrant — this creates the logical scaffold before detail is added.",
                "Replace continent-based thinking with climate-based thinking: for each biome, write the climate definition first, then list continents as examples. Never write 'rainforest = Amazon' without first writing 'rainforest = warm (>25°C) and very wet (>2000mm/year)'.",
                "For adaptations: always write 'natural selection favoured...' rather than 'the organism developed...' — this forces correct evolutionary framing from the start.",
                "For the soil paradox: draw two columns — 'where the nutrients are' vs 'where we assume nutrients are'. In rainforest: nutrients are in biomass, not soil. In temperate grassland: nutrients are in soil (mollisol). Redraw until automatic.",
                "Make a two-row comparison table: desertification (human-caused, reversible with management, occurs at biome margins) vs natural desert (climate-defined, stable, occurs in specific climate zones)."
            ],
            misconceptionsToAddress: [
                "Biome = continent → climate-first definition drill (above)",
                "Tropical soil = fertile → nutrient location diagram (above)",
                "Adaptation = choice → natural selection language habit (above)"
            ]
        },

        developing: {
            characteristics: [
                "Correctly places most biomes on the Whittaker diagram but confuses the boreal/temperate boundary",
                "Can state climate conditions for each biome but struggles to explain why those conditions produce that vegetation structure",
                "Identifies adaptations correctly but classifies structural and physiological types inconsistently",
                "Understands feedback inhibition and climate change biome shift as concepts but cannot trace the mechanism step by step",
                "Can name human impacts on biomes but cannot quantify or prioritise them"
            ],
            immediateNextSteps: [
                "For Whittaker diagram accuracy: focus on the boreal vs temperate boundary — boreal is distinguished by permafrost, shorter growing season (<90 days), and coniferous dominance despite similar precipitation to temperate. Write these three distinguishing criteria on a flashcard and test against the diagram.",
                "For climate→vegetation causality: practise 'because chains' — 'tropical rainforest has a closed canopy because rainfall is year-round, which means light reaches the ground year-round, which means it is worth plants investing in climbing (lianas) and epiphytism to access it.' Write a because-chain for each biome.",
                "For adaptation classification: build a three-column table (structural / physiological / behavioural) with five examples in each column from five different biomes. Focus on distinguishing physiological (internal metabolic — CAM photosynthesis, antifreeze proteins) from structural (physical form — needle leaves, waxy cuticle).",
                "For climate change biome shift: draw the mechanism as a flow diagram — warming → snowline rises → alpine tundra area shrinks → specialist species lose habitat → local extinction — rather than describing it in prose. Flow diagrams force step-by-step mechanistic thinking.",
                "For human impact prioritisation: rank the five human impacts (deforestation, agriculture, fragmentation, invasive species, desertification) by hectares affected globally. Look up current estimates. This replaces vague qualitative understanding with quantified comparison."
            ],
            misconceptionsToAddress: [
                "Boreal vs temperate confusion → three distinguishing criteria flashcard (above)",
                "Structural vs physiological adaptation confusion → three-column classification table (above)",
                "Climate change as gradual uniform warming → flow diagram showing mechanism (above)"
            ]
        },

        proficient: {
            characteristics: [
                "Correctly constructs and interprets a Whittaker diagram, positioning all seven biomes accurately",
                "Explains the climate→soil→vegetation→animal community chain for each biome with mechanistic accuracy",
                "Classifies adaptations correctly across all three types and connects each to a specific biome pressure",
                "Explains convergent evolution with specific examples from multiple biomes",
                "Analyses human impacts on biomes using quantitative data and ecological principles (species-area relationship, fragmentation theory)",
                "Can trace the carbon feedback loop from permafrost thaw to accelerated warming"
            ],
            immediateNextSteps: [
                "Extend analysis to aquatic biomes: compare NPP and biodiversity across coral reef, open ocean, estuary, and freshwater lake — explain why productivity differs so dramatically between adjacent marine systems.",
                "Apply island biogeography theory (MacArthur-Wilson) to fragmented biome patches: calculate expected species richness for patches of different sizes using the species-area relationship (S = cA^z) and evaluate what minimum patch size supports viable populations of large-ranging mammals.",
                "Research the latitudinal diversity gradient — the increase in species richness toward the equator — and evaluate the three leading explanations (productivity hypothesis, evolutionary time hypothesis, climate stability hypothesis) against the evidence.",
                "Connect biome carbon stocks to IPCC climate projections: look up published estimates of carbon stored in tropical forest, boreal peat, and tundra permafrost, and calculate what fraction of the remaining 1.5°C carbon budget would be committed if each store released 20% of its carbon.",
                "Investigate phenological mismatch as a consequence of biome warming — research one documented case (e.g. oak leafing date vs winter moth caterpillar emergence vs great tit chick hatching) and trace the trophic cascade consequences."
            ],
            misconceptionsToAddress: [
                "All marine systems are similarly productive → coral reef vs open ocean NPP comparison (above)",
                "Biome shift = simple boundary movement → rate-of-species-migration vs rate-of-climate-change comparison"
            ]
        },

        expert: {
            characteristics: [
                "Critically evaluates the Whittaker biome classification system, identifying what it cannot account for (fire, seasonality, soils, evolutionary history)",
                "Applies quantitative ecological models (species-area relationship, NPP equations, carbon flux budgets) to biome analysis",
                "Synthesises across biomes to identify global patterns (latitudinal diversity gradient, productivity-precipitation relationship, soil formation rates)",
                "Evaluates conservation interventions against ecological theory and real-world constraints",
                "Connects biome biology to Earth system feedbacks (albedo, evapotranspiration, carbon cycling) at the global scale"
            ],
            immediateNextSteps: [
                "Critically evaluate the Whittaker classification: identify three real locations where predicted biome does not match realised biome, determine the additional variable(s) explaining the discrepancy, and propose how the classification could be extended to account for them.",
                "Model the species-area relationship for a specific fragmentation scenario: given initial forest area of 10,000 km² reduced to ten patches of 100 km² each, calculate the expected long-term species loss using S = cA^z (with z = 0.25, typical for continental fragments) and evaluate the conservation implications.",
                "Investigate the concept of biome tipping points quantitatively: read the Lenton et al. (2008) tipping elements paper and evaluate which biome-related tipping elements are most at risk under current emissions trajectories, with specific temperature thresholds where known.",
                "Apply the metabolic scaling theory to compare NPP across biomes: research the relationship between temperature, leaf area index, and NPP, and evaluate whether a simple temperature-driven model can account for the full NPP range from tundra to tropical rainforest."
            ],
            misconceptionsToAddress: [
                "Whittaker diagram as perfect biome predictor → three-case discrepancy analysis (above)",
                "Conservation = protecting existing biomes → evaluate restoration and assisted migration as complementary strategies"
            ]
        }
    }
